The Crystal Place
Perhapers the most extrodunary buildings in the nineteenth century was the Crystal Place, which was built in the Haid Park for the great exhibition of 1851. The Crystal Place was different from all other buildings for it was made of iron and glass. It was one of the biggist buildings in all time and a lot of people from many countries came to see it. A great many products from various parts of the world were sent to the exibition. There was also a great deal of machinary on display. The most wonderful machinary was Nansmith's steam harmor. Though in those days, travelling was not as easy as it is today, steam boats carried thousands of vistors accros the channel from Europe. There were six thousand vistors in all and all the profits were used to build musiums and collages. Later, the Crystal Place were moved to South Londong. It remained one of the most famous buildings in the world until it was burn down in 1936.
